    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the whimsy. Let's focus on the science, shall we?\n\nThe Maillard reaction is a non-enzymatic browning reaction that occurs when amino acids and reducing sugars are exposed to heat. It's a complex process involving the breakdown and recombination of these molecules, resulting in the formation of new compounds with distinct flavors, colors, and aromas.\n\nNow, to answer your original question, the Maillard reaction is most pronounced between 140°C to 180°C (284°F to 356°F). This is because, within this temperature range, the amino acids and reducing sugars are able to break down and recombine in a way that creates those beautiful, golden-brown colors and flavors. At lower temperatures, the reaction is slower and less pronounced, but it can still occur, especially when food is cooked for extended periods or at lower heat levels.\n\nFor example, when cooking a steak, the Maillard reaction can start to occur at around 120°C to 130°C (248°F to 266°F), but it's not until the steak is seared at higher temperatures, around 140°C to 150°C (284°F to 302°F), that the reaction really kicks in",
